title: Want To Buy:  Pistols/Revolvers/Handguns
postcontent:
Collector wants to buy another handgun.
I prefer NIB, or LNIB, with all manuals and packaging.
I will consider others, but understandably will offer a little less.
I prefer 40's and 45's, but will consider others.
In case you haven't noticed, it's no longer a seller's market.
Guns are a dime a dozen now.  It's not like it was 6 months ago.
Private sellers that want more than they paid for their guns, still own their guns.
I pay FAIR used prices (about 20% less than NEW retail) for used handguns.
A used handgun is one that is not purchased new from a dealer.
And a NIB handgun from a private party is a used handgun.
I live in Yakima and will only do a face to face deal.
I may meet a seller 1/2 way in a public place if the deal is right.

title: For Sale:  C2  Taser
postcontent: I'm selling my C2 taser.  For those that do not know, this is the civilian version of the police taser.  Aside from ergonomic differences, the police model does a 10 second burst to allow them to put handcuffs on the assailant while the civilian model does a 30 second burst to allow you to leave your taser on the ground and escape without further conflict. Taser International has a policy to replace your taser for free if you submit to them a valid police report stating that you had to use your taser in such a manner. These are legal to conceal carry in Kent county without a permit.  I'm selling because I recently moved to New Castle county where I cannot legally carry it.  Taser lists the battery as having enough power for about 50 uses, I've used it about 15 times just testing it so there's plenty of life left in the battery.  I'm including a holster, 2 live cartridges and 1 blue trainer cartridge.  This is the newer model that is equipped with a flashlight and laser sight.  You can remove the cartridge and use it as a basic stun-gun that shocks on contact instead of using the projectile cartridges. There is no transfer fee or FFL required to buy this, I just need your information to submit to Taser so they can update the registration on the device.  I paid about $375 for it and used one cartridge to test.  I'm asking $250 and I'm located in Newark. I work in Dover most days so I'd easily be able to meet up with a Kent County resident to sell it.  Cash is preferable but I'm open to trades as well.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Stoeger, Full Stainless - 9mm, Luger Action Pistol
postcontent:
This is a hard to find, classically designed and as nicely a detailed handgun as you will find anywhere.  I am the original owner and have cared for it like a baby.  It is a luger action, meaning it ejects the shells from the top and feeds to the center of the gun, and has no slide at all.  It was originally designed in WW2 by the German Army.  This is Stoeger's version brought up to date and flawlessly executed in the modern age.  It is in like-new, perfect condition and has probably only had 150 or so rounds fired through it.  It is a fun gun and a blast to shoot.  I am interested in any trades and will entertain all offers.

Note:
Last night I had 7 auctions flagged as a scam. I don't appreciate that at all as this is no scam and is 100% legitimate. A listing takes a long time to list in total and I hate having to relist auctions for no reason. I am an honorable member of this forum and have many people that I can reference who I have personally done business with here before. Please contact me before flagging any post of mine as it is not fair to me or potential buyers and I do not fraudulently post anything, ever. Thank you and have a nice day.

title: For Trade:  Polish PPS-43C Pistol- Automatic, BRAND NEW IN BOX WITH FOUR (4) MAGAZINES
postcontent:
Polish PPS-43C in a semi-auto version. 7.62x25 caliber, considered a pistol due to overall length. Comes with FOUR - 35rd mag. 
The PPS-43C (Pistolet-Pulemet Sudaeva, model of 1943 = Sudaev SMG) was born as an answer to the need for a weapon that is more compact and mobile than the PPSh-41, then in use by the Soviet Army. The PPSh-41 was somewhat too long to be used by tank crews and mobile recon groups and paratroopers, so late in 1941, the Red Army issued a request for a new more compact sub machine gun (SMG). The designer Sudaev initially designed his new SMG in 1942, and it was adopted under the designation of PPS-42. The next year he refined the design, and this final model was designated as the PPS-43. This model was manufactured in significant numbers (nearly two million PPS-43 weapons were manufactured between 1943 and 1946). The PPS-43 is sometimes referred to as the best SMG of World War II. After WWII, it was widely exported to pro-Soviet regimes around the world, and widely copied. This historical firearm has been re-designed to shoot from a closed bolt position. The safety is located at the front of the trigger guard. The receiver and barrel shroud are made from stamped steel. The rear sight is an L-shaped flip type and is marked for 100 and 200 meters, the front sight is a fixed blade type. The barrel is equipped with a simple muzzle brake. This firearm is an ATF approved pistol. The stock has no function and is permanently fixed in its folded position. 

This pistol is manufactured at the famed Radom Plant in Poland. 
All parts and components are new and Polish made.

The Ruger 10/22 is one of the most popular 22 rifles in the world and many types of scopes and mounts are available for this handy little carbine. Many of the compact and mini-scopes being manufactured today rival the performance of full size scopes while offering lighter weight and smaller profiles. These features make them ideal for rim fire and other small caliber sporting rifles and, even though the eye relief on these mini-scopes equals that of the full size scopes, they do present a problem. Because of their short length, they need to be mounted further back on the receiver.

Most Weaver style scope mounts were made to accommodate full size scopes on high power rifles and don’t work well on smaller 22s. Until recently, there were few mounts made that could effectively accommodate the smaller mini-scopes while still maintaining proper eye relief.

We have a unique, reversible Picatinny rail scope mount for the Ruger 10/22 rim fire rifle that can be installed in two positions. In the forward position it accommodates the longer full size scopes, but when the mount is reversed, a mini-scope can be mounted further back to obtain a full field of view.

We installed this Picatinny rail mount on several of our Ruger 10/22s and mounted a variety of fixed and variable power mini-scopes using different types and brands of scope rings. The result of these experiments were several Ruger 10/22 packages, including this kit, which offer great values for hunters and target shooters.

Leave the power set on 3x or 4x in the field and you’re ready for close-in fast moving targets. title: For Trade:  800 Rounds Federal HST .40S&W JHP
location: Puyallup (in Spokane for the weekend), Washington, United States
postcontent:
Best CCW Ammo you can buy!

For sale/trade is 800 rounds of Federal HST 155gr JHP for a .40S&W.

Federal released its Hydra-Shok line of ammunition to capture the law enforcement market years ago, and while it was a good round - it proved troublesome when going through barriers before reaching its target - clogging much of the time.

Federal corrected the problem by introducing a line known as HST, and it was tested extensively by the FBI upon its release in .40 caliber, and adopted as their ammunition after blowing the tests out of the water. This is currently the only ammunition I will carry as I feel like it is the only ammunition to hold a candle to the famous "Black Talon".

It's easy to find the much less desirable Hydra-Shok ammunition on the shelf, and many people are intrigued by the "post" inside the hollow point. If you do the research, and I suggest you do, you will find that HST is extremely tough to beat.

That's why HST has almost never (in my experience) been for sale on the shelves at your local gun shop - I have only ever found it online, for a premium price, and in small or limited quantities. I have recently switched to a different caliber for my preferred CCW and cannot find anywhere that sells HST in bulk, must less a place with a single box in stock right now.

I live in Puyallup, but will be willing to drive a reasonable distance to meet - or even ship if you want to pay for shipping. I will also be in Spokane for the holiday weekend and can meet there.

Take a look here for FBI Protocol test results on this ammunition
http://le.atk.com/ammunition/federal/handgun/details.aspx?id=567

title: For Sale:  French Berthier MLE 1907/15 - 8mm Lebel, Restored, Nice!!
postcontent:
This rifle was a  display piece in my office for many years until my company finally asked me to remove it. 

I obtained it in 1985 from a neighbor. This gentleman was retired and his full time hobby and passion was restoring old military guns  - mostly rifles and pistols from the turn of the century up to WWII. 

He did the work in his garage and he had pallets full of old guns  and gun parts. He always said his goal was to make the old guns beautiful again. 

This particular rifle is a Bethier Model 1907/15 made by Chatellerault in 1927. It's chambered in 8mm LEBEL and ammo is still available at a reasonable cost from PPU, Graf, Hornady and a few others. 

My old neighbor told me this rifle was mechanically able to be fired, but I must insist that you have the rifle examined by a gunsmith before you do. At 86 years old it's simply the prudent thing to do.  

The condition of the rifle is fantastic as it has been completely restored. It's really a thing of beauty and the attention to detail that went into it is terrific. 

I'm really not sure how my neighbor refinished the metal, but it appears to be some sort of black phosphate to me. It's definitely not blued, and this would have been done well before the days of DuraCoat and similar.  

The wood appears to have a hand rubbed oil finish. Bore is very good and everything fits together quite well. Action is tight and everything seems 100% functional. 

The rifle comes with an original French "knitting needle" style brass grip bayonet, and a beautiful sling that I assume is a reproduction, but one that was obviously made 30+ years ago since it was on the rifle when I bought it in 1985. 

Additionally there are 4 original charger clips and 20 rounds of original ammo that also came with the gun. 

I'm asking $600 and think this rifle is worth every penny. Rifle is to be picked up in Brandon by a Florida resident who is at least 18 years old. 

Thanks for looking.
